        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Algorithm Structure

            For an array of size n:

            - Outer loop runs from 0 to n-1
            - Inner loop finds minimum from i to n-1
            - Swap elements

            Pseudo logic:

            for i = 0 to n-1  
                min_index = i  
                for j = i+1 to n-1  
                    if arr[j] < arr[min_index]  
                        min_index = j  
                swap(arr[i], arr[min_index])
            </script>



          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Number of Comparisons

            Selection Sort always performs:

            (n - 1) + (n - 2) + ... + 1 comparisons

            Which equals:

            #### n(n - 1) / 2 ####

            Time Complexity:

            - Best Case: O(n²)
            - Average Case: O(n²)
            - Worst Case: O(n²)
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Swaps Analysis

            Unlike Bubble Sort:

            - Maximum of n - 1 swaps
            - Swaps only once per outer iteration

            Useful when:
            - Swapping is expensive
            - Memory writes must be minimized
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Space Complexity

            Selection Sort is:

            - In-place algorithm
            - Requires O(1) extra space

            It does not:
            - Create auxiliary arrays
            - Use recursion
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Is It Stable?

            Standard Selection Sort is:

            ❌ Not stable

            Example:

            [4a, 4b, 2]

            After sorting:
            [2, 4b, 4a]

            Relative order changed.
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # When Should You Use It?

            Good for:

            - Small datasets
            - Educational purposes
            - Situations with costly swaps

            Not recommended for:

            - Large datasets
            - Performance-critical systems
            </script>
          </div>
