        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Exercise: Implement Selection Sort

            ## Objective

            Implement the **Selection Sort** algorithm from scratch.

            You must sort a list of integers in ascending order without using built-in sorting functions.

            ---

            ## Problem

            Given the list:

            [29, 10, 14, 37, 13]

            Write a function:

            selection_sort(arr)

            that returns the sorted list.

            ---

            ## Required Steps

            Follow these algorithm steps carefully:

            1. Start at index i = 0
            2. Assume the minimum element is at position i
            3. Scan the rest of the array (from i+1 to end)
            4. Update the minimum index if a smaller value is found
            5. Swap the element at index i with the minimum element
            6. Move to the next position (i = i + 1)
            7. Repeat until the array is sorted

            ---

            ## Algorithm Flow

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Start at i] --> B[Assume min = i];
              B --> C[Scan rest of array];
              C --> D{Smaller found?};
              D -- Yes --> E[Update min index];
              D -- No --> F[Continue scanning];
              E --> C;
              F --> G[Swap arr[i] with arr[min]];
              G --> H[Increment i];
              H --> I{End of array?};
              I -- No --> B;
              I -- Yes --> J[Finished];
            /mermaid

            ---

            ## Complexity Reminder

            Selection Sort performs:

            #### n(n - 1) / 2 ####

            comparisons, which means:

            Time Complexity = O(n²)

            ---

            ## Your Task

            - Implement the function
            - Do not use sorted() or list.sort()
            - Test your solution with different inputs
            - Try printing the array after each pass to observe progress

            ---

            spoiler
            ```
            def selection_sort(arr):
                n = len(arr)
                
                for i in range(n):
                    min_index = i
                    
                    for j in range(i + 1, n):
                        if arr[j] < arr[min_index]:
                            min_index = j
                    
                    # Swap the found minimum element with the first unsorted element
                    arr[i], arr[min_index] = arr[min_index], arr[i]
                
                return arr


            # Example usage
            numbers = [29, 10, 14, 37, 13]
            sorted_numbers = selection_sort(numbers)

            print("Sorted list:", sorted_numbers)
            ```
            /spoiler
